    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Why So Many Disabled Workers?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ben Sheerer letter, commenting on September 2 article on rising cost of disability pay, disputes assertion that rolls are swollen because laid-off workers are choosing not to look for new jobs</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A Sept. 2 front-page article implies that the disability rolls are swollen because laid-off workers are choosing not to look for new jobs. As a lawyer who handles disability cases, I find that most people keep working until they no longer can or until their employer forces them to leave because of their inability to do the job.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A Sept. 2 front-page article implies that the disability rolls are swollen because laid-off workers are choosing not to look for new jobs. As a lawyer who handles disability cases, I find that most people keep working until they no longer can or until their employer forces them to leave because of their inability to do the job.</p>
        <p>The excessive time it takes to apply for and receive Social Security disability payments is a national scandal. Before checks start arriving, many workers lose their houses and cars and find themselves dependent on their children.</p>
        <p>BEN SHEERER  Cleveland, Sept. 2, 2002</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
